squeezed down to their essence.

249
00:26:38,974 --> 00:26:43,520
The raw pulp of truth, my truth,
in one transcendent narrative.

250
00:26:44,688 --> 00:26:46,482
Is that where the "whoroborus" came in?

251
00:26:47,024 --> 00:26:48,942
Keep pushing me, I'll quit.

252
00:26:53,822 --> 00:26:55,199
No, you won't.

253
00:26:55,991 --> 00:26:58,327
You'll drink your cocktails,
make your idle threats,

254
00:26:58,494 --> 00:27:00,120
and get this out of your system.

255
00:27:00,287 --> 00:27:01,497
But don't take too long.

256
00:27:01,872 --> 00:27:03,874
If Ford can't pull this off,

257
00:27:04,041 --> 00:27:06,168
the board will be
looking for a replacement.

258
00:27:08,337 --> 00:27:10,047
But they won't be looking here.

259
00:27:24,853 --> 00:27:27,564
Fastest way to get to Wyatt, you said.

260
00:27:28,357 --> 00:27:31,026
But it doesn't look like they're
letting anyone pass here, either.

261
00:27:31,235 --> 00:27:33,153
There's fewer soldiers than Pariah.

262
00:27:33,737 --> 00:27:36,740
<i>We shoot our way through. That
tunnel leads to the Old Territories.</i>

263
00:27:37,324 --> 00:27:39,076
My, my, Teddy.

264
00:27:39,326 --> 00:27:41,495
I think Robert gave you
some extra vinegar back there.

265
00:27:41,662 --> 00:27:43,497
Maybe took away some sense, too.

266
00:27:43,997 --> 00:27:45,582
Doesn't matter how fast the route is,

267
00:27:45,749 --> 00:27:48,585
if you're gonna end up dead
in the middle of it.

268
00:27:49,920 --> 00:27:53,340
I need you to find Wyatt.

269
00:28:21,243 --> 00:28:24,913
At ease, fellas.
Keep up the exemplary work.

270
00:28:31,295 --> 00:28:32,296
Wyatt's handiwork.

271
00:28:32,880 --> 00:28:34,298
<i>How can you tell?</i>

272
00:28:34,464 --> 00:28:36,800
Straight-up killing
couldn't hold his interest,

273
00:28:37,718 --> 00:28:40,637
like he wasn't living up
to the full measure of his calling.

274
00:28:41,138 --> 00:28:42,764
So, he worked to get more creative.

275
00:28:44,308 --> 00:28:46,810
<i>It's Wyatt all right. He's close.</i>

276
00:28:47,311 --> 00:28:48,645
A word of advice.

277
00:28:48,979 --> 00:28:52,399
Whatever your past indiscretions,
make peace with them.

278
00:28:52,566 --> 00:28:55,485
They're only gonna get worse
the further along we go.

279
00:28:57,654 --> 00:28:58,655
Flood?

280
00:29:00,157 --> 00:29:02,367
Fuck me. That's Teddy Flood.

281
00:29:04,995 --> 00:29:06,496
You've made a mistake, soldier.

282
00:29:06,830 --> 00:29:08,630
But it's not too late
for you to keep walking.

283
00:29:08,665 --> 00:29:11,126
All due respect, sir,
that's a face I'll never forget.

284
00:29:11,293 --> 00:29:14,129
That's the son of a bitch
who ambushed our outpost at Escalante.

285
00:29:16,632 --> 00:29:18,985
You don't know a damn thing
about what went down in Escalante.

286
00:29:19,009 --> 00:29:21,511
I know Wyatt didn't kill
all those men by himself,

287
00:29:21,678 --> 00:29:24,038
and I know a thing or two
about what's going down right now.

288
00:29:28,143 --> 00:29:29,503
You trying to get yourself killed?

289
00:29:29,686 --> 00:29:31,313
Making peace with past indiscretions.

290
00:29:31,939 --> 00:29:33,941
Go! I'll hold them off.

291
00:29:52,167 --> 00:29:53,961
Jesus.

292
00:29:56,880 --> 00:29:59,049
- What would you like?
- Water, please.

293
00:30:00,634 --> 00:30:03,345
You look like a woman
who could use a drink.

294
00:30:05,222 --> 00:30:06,515
What's your poison?

295
00:30:06,974 --> 00:30:11,228
I've been here enough to know that
the park is all the poison I can handle.

296
00:30:11,520 --> 00:30:15,565
Mmm. A repeat visitor. Traveling solo?

297
00:30:16,984 --> 00:30:19,903
<i>Purist. Getting off
on the undiluted experience.</i>

298
00:30:21,071 --> 00:30:23,740
Your favorite narrative is... Oh...

299
00:30:26,952 --> 00:30:28,578
"The Final Burial of Salvation."

300
00:30:29,705 --> 00:30:30,747
How did you know?

301
00:30:30,914 --> 00:30:34,751
It's my business to read desires
and to satiate them.

302
00:30:35,002 --> 00:30:39,047
Erm... I'm Lee. Lee Sizemore.

303
00:30:39,631 --> 00:30:40,924
Head of Narrative.

304
00:30:41,091 --> 00:30:43,760
All these fantasies
come from your twisted little mind, huh?

305
00:30:43,927 --> 00:30:46,555
Well, the good ones do.

306
00:30:47,764 --> 00:30:50,559
So, tell me, Mr. Sizemore...

307
00:30:50,976 --> 00:30:52,310
What's your favorite ride?

308
00:30:53,103 --> 00:30:55,772
Well, I write them. I don't play them.

309
00:30:55,939 --> 00:30:58,650
Oh, you want others to indulge,
but you won't do so yourself?

310
00:30:59,776 --> 00:31:01,111
You're afraid to lose control.

311
00:31:05,449 --> 00:31:09,578
Maybe... Maybe it's just a product
of my work environment.

312
00:31:10,120 --> 00:31:12,789
We're not exactly in a culture
where we can just let loose.

313
00:31:12,998 --> 00:31:15,643
I would've thought the head of narrative
could do whatever he wanted.

314
00:31:15,667 --> 00:31:18,837
My artistic freedom is constrained,

315
00:31:19,046 --> 00:31:20,839
what with QA breathing down my neck

316
00:31:21,006 --> 00:31:23,467
and Behavior programming
the damn things to go off-script.

317
00:31:24,468 --> 00:31:26,344
The robots can go off-script?

318
00:31:27,012 --> 00:31:28,472
Just little gestures.

319
00:31:28,638 --> 00:31:30,807
You know, supposedly
it makes the things more lifelike.

320
00:31:30,974 --> 00:31:32,350
But really...

321
00:31:32,809 --> 00:31:36,646
It's just a vanity project from
the megalomaniac who started this place.

322
00:31:36,813 --> 00:31:40,484
Yeah, frankly, I don't know why
the suits at Delos put up with him.

323
00:31:44,946 --> 00:31:46,826
Sorry. I'm afraid
I'm gonna have to cut you off.

324
00:31:47,532 --> 00:31:48,867
Do you know who I am?

325
00:31:49,659 --> 00:31:52,120
I do. Ms. Cullen told me to find you
and relay a message.

326
00:31:52,704 --> 00:31:55,540
<i>"Tortured artist only works for artists.</i>

327
00:31:56,166 --> 00:31:57,834
"Sober up and get back to work."

328
00:31:58,710 --> 00:32:00,295
It seems you're busy.

329
00:32:02,339 --> 00:32:04,633
- Look me up later?
- Well, I don't even know your--

330
00:32:13,308 --> 00:32:14,559
Fuck this job.

331
00:32:17,104 --> 00:32:18,105
What are you working on?

332
00:32:18,522 --> 00:32:19,922
Nothing of note. Business as usual.

333
00:32:21,149 --> 00:32:24,194
Keeping up appearances before
we bust this stray shit wide open?

334
00:32:26,905 --> 00:32:28,865
I'm close to finding our saboteur.

335
00:32:29,366 --> 00:32:32,202
That tracking data you gave me?
It's time-stamped.

336
00:32:32,410 --> 00:32:34,290
But once I cross-reference it
with SAT tracking,

337
00:32:34,412 --> 00:32:37,582
we're gonna figure out who programmed
him to try to smuggle out our data.

338
00:32:37,749 --> 00:32:38,750
Excellent.

339
00:32:39,709 --> 00:32:41,002
Look.

340
00:32:42,045 --> 00:32:44,214
When our corporate overlords realize

341
00:32:44,381 --> 00:32:47,592
that we have saved them
from corporate espionage,

342
00:32:47,759 --> 00:32:48,959
they are going to be grateful.

343
00:32:49,386 --> 00:32:53,557
And I am going to accept their gratitude
in the form of a title bump,

344
00:32:53,723 --> 00:32:57,227
a room upgrade,
and unlimited Mesa Bar access.

345
00:32:58,103 --> 00:32:59,783
Maybe I should request
Theresa's quarters.

346
00:32:59,938 --> 00:33:02,732
You know the first head to roll
for all this is gonna be hers.

347
00:33:02,899 --> 00:33:04,734
Yeah, don't be so disappointed for her.

348
00:33:04,901 --> 00:33:06,403
You reap what you sow.

349
00:33:06,903 --> 00:33:09,239
If QA spent less time
treating us like the enemy--

350
00:33:09,406 --> 00:33:12,200
That's a two-way street, Elsie.
Theresa's just trying to do her job.

351
00:33:12,367 --> 00:33:13,785
Maybe she should try harder.

352
00:33:14,744 --> 00:33:17,344
Sure seems like there's a lot of shit
slipping through the cracks.

353
00:33:39,227 --> 00:33:40,896
Got it. Okay.

354
00:33:41,980 --> 00:33:43,982
- Good afternoon.
- Good afternoon.

355
00:33:44,149 --> 00:33:45,734
Any progress on the inquiry I sent?

356
00:33:45,942 --> 00:33:48,612
Yes, Mr. Lowe.
I've got the information you asked for.

357
00:33:48,778 --> 00:33:52,490
As expected, there are neither guests
nor hosts registered in that sector.

358
00:33:52,657 --> 00:33:53,950
"As expected"?

359
00:33:54,576 --> 00:33:57,621
It's been designated off-limits
for future narrative development.

360
00:33:57,787 --> 00:34:00,290
Have any techs visited
Sector 17 recently?

361
00:34:01,291 --> 00:34:03,084
Checking.

362
00:34:03,251 --> 00:34:04,294
No one.

363
00:35:46,813 --> 00:35:48,815
Are you Arnold?

364
00:35:51,985 --> 00:35:53,403
Who's Arnold?

365
00:35:54,237 --> 00:35:55,572
And who the hell are you?

366
00:35:56,740 --> 00:35:59,492
<i>Boy? Is this some friend of yours?</i>

367
00:36:00,660 --> 00:36:02,078
Well, you're trespassing.

368
00:36:02,245 --> 00:36:03,496
Freeze motor functions.

369
00:36:05,540 --> 00:36:08,877
- I said freeze all motor functions.
- Daddy... Don't hurt him. He's just lost.

370
00:36:09,044 --> 00:36:12,339
Well, he can be lost on
someone else's property, can't you?

371
00:36:12,505 --> 00:36:13,757
That's enough.

372
00:36:15,592 --> 00:36:16,593
As you were.

373
00:36:24,267 --> 00:36:26,102
They don't respond to voice commands.

374
00:36:26,269 --> 00:36:27,854
Well, they do respond to mine.

375
00:36:29,189 --> 00:36:30,357
Who are they?

376
00:36:31,274 --> 00:36:32,609
Ghosts now.

377
00:36:33,943 --> 00:36:36,780
<i>Survivors of the wreck of time.</i>

378
00:36:39,532 --> 00:36:41,409
These are first-generation?

379
00:36:41,910 --> 00:36:42,952
Come here, boy.

380
00:36:49,292 --> 00:36:50,710
Turn the other cheek.

381
00:36:58,968 --> 00:37:02,055
<i>See, what our newer designs
gained in efficiency,</i>

382
00:37:02,222 --> 00:37:04,641
they lost in grace.

383
00:37:05,642 --> 00:37:08,269
How are they still operating
after all this time?

384
00:37:08,645 --> 00:37:10,230
I maintain them myself.

385
00:37:12,065 --> 00:37:13,108
That's enough, Robert.

386
00:37:18,488 --> 00:37:22,826
These are the only ones left in the park
that Arnold built himself.

387
00:37:24,494 --> 00:37:26,621
That's why I didn't have the heart
to destroy them.

388
00:37:27,330 --> 00:37:28,665
That, and the obvious.

389
00:37:29,666 --> 00:37:31,418
<i>Hello, Jock. Good boy.</i>

390
00:37:33,837 --> 00:37:36,506
<i>I told him of a holiday
my family had taken once,</i>

391
00:37:36,673 --> 00:37:39,175
<i>out on the seaside at
Pendeen in Cornwall.</i>

392
00:37:39,843 --> 00:37:43,179
My brother and I roamed the countryside.

393
00:37:46,015 --> 00:37:48,518
It was my only happy memory
of my childhood.

394
00:37:51,312 --> 00:37:53,440
<i>And Arnold built them as a gift.</i>

395
00:37:53,606 --> 00:37:58,486
<i>He said that great artists
always hid themselves in their work.</i>

396
00:37:58,653 --> 00:38:03,199
Of course, Arnold's versions
flattered the originals.

397
00:38:03,700 --> 00:38:06,286
<i>I made some adjustments over the years.</i>

398
00:38:06,453 --> 00:38:11,791
Gave my father, in particular,
a few of his original characteristics.

399
00:38:13,209 --> 00:38:16,838
Respectfully, sir,
this sort of thing troubles me.

400
00:38:17,881 --> 00:38:19,841
Unmonitored hosts in the park?

401
00:38:20,008 --> 00:38:21,551
<i>They only go where I've let them.</i>

402
00:38:21,801 --> 00:38:24,554
They're quite harmless,
like all our hosts.

403
00:38:25,555 --> 00:38:28,725
I'm sure you can indulge me
the little connection with my past.

404
00:38:29,893 --> 00:38:32,228
If you could only
see your son again, Bernard.

405
00:38:33,813 --> 00:38:35,231
Wouldn't you want to?

406
00:38:40,862 --> 00:38:42,572
I think I should be getting back.

407
00:38:42,739 --> 00:38:45,825
Yes. Talk about this later, if you like.

408
00:38:50,079 --> 00:38:51,498
<i>Well, Robert.</i>

409
00:38:52,707 --> 00:38:54,501
Tell me all about your day.

410
00:39:05,261 --> 00:39:09,057
Keep your eye on Pariah.
We're running close to capacity tonight.

411
00:39:11,267 --> 00:39:13,228
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

412
00:39:13,436 --> 00:39:16,439
Looks like acid rain on Sweetwater!

413
00:39:17,106 --> 00:39:20,777
<i>Fuck Ford and his new fucking narrative!</i>

414
00:39:20,944 --> 00:39:23,613
Fuck this stupid fucking map!

415
00:39:24,239 --> 00:39:27,909
Fuck that teetotaling Danish bitch.

416
00:39:28,284 --> 00:39:31,079
Are you filing a complaint,
Mr. Sizemore?

417
00:39:33,456 --> 00:39:39,462
I am declaring that this park is my stage,
and I shall do with it what I please.

418
00:39:39,629 --> 00:39:42,215
Well, I suppose
now is as good a time as any.

419
00:39:42,382 --> 00:39:44,759
Lee Sizemore, this is Charlotte Hale,

420
00:39:46,094 --> 00:39:48,304
the Executive Director of our board.

421
00:39:48,471 --> 00:39:52,976
She's here on behalf of Delos to oversee
certain transitions in our administration.

422
00:39:59,649 --> 00:40:00,817
We've met.

423
00:40:08,324 --> 00:40:10,577
<i>Access host resources logs.</i>

424
00:40:11,327 --> 00:40:13,121
How many first-generation
hosts are there?

425
00:40:13,288 --> 00:40:14,622
<i>Eighty-two.</i>

426
00:40:14,789 --> 00:40:17,125
And how many of those
were designed by Arnold?

427
00:40:17,792 --> 00:40:19,168
<i>Forty-seven.</i>

428
00:40:19,627 --> 00:40:21,129
List the names, alphabetically,

429
00:40:21,296 --> 00:40:23,965
of all first-generation hosts
still in rotation.

430
00:40:43,109 --> 00:40:44,694
Be smart about this, fellas.

431
00:40:45,111 --> 00:40:49,032
<i>I understand the visceral pleasure
of revenge more than most,</i>

432
00:40:49,282 --> 00:40:51,284
but I'm prepared to do business here.

433
00:40:52,160 --> 00:40:55,371
<i>This man is very valuable to me,
alive and well.</i>

434
00:40:55,538 --> 00:40:59,167
If you don't quiet down,
I'm liable to add you to the herd,

435
00:41:00,835 --> 00:41:02,712
along with your buddy Flood here.

436
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:07,800
<i>You're a traitorous son of a bitch
and a coldhearted killer, Flood.</i>

437
00:41:37,205 --> 00:41:38,915
You're right. I am a killer.

438
00:42:00,687 --> 00:42:02,605
Grab a horse!
Let's get the fuck out of here!

439
00:42:03,106 --> 00:42:04,524
They'll just follow us.

440
00:42:47,567 --> 00:42:49,110
You think you know someone.

441
00:42:49,944 --> 00:42:51,487
You don't know me at all.

442
00:42:58,244 --> 00:43:00,496
<i>Let's get our horses
and gear and move on.</i>

443
00:43:14,302 --> 00:43:16,429
- Elsie.
- I identified the satellite.

444
00:43:16,596 --> 00:43:17,847
- It's one of ours.
<i>- What?</i>

445
00:43:18,014 --> 00:43:19,849
It's a fucking Delos satellite.

446
00:43:20,475 --> 00:43:22,075
Whatever we're on to is some heavy shit.

447
00:43:22,143 --> 00:43:24,246
Oh, get this, that bicameral system
you told me about?

448
00:43:24,270 --> 00:43:25,831
I think that's what they used
to hack the woodcutter.

449
00:43:25,855 --> 00:43:27,690
<i>The voices our hosts have been hearing?</i>

450
00:43:27,857 --> 00:43:29,776
<i>I think someone's been
broadcasting to them.</i>

451
00:43:29,942 --> 00:43:31,527
We abandoned that system decades ago.

452
00:43:31,694 --> 00:43:33,464
Yeah, well, there are still relays
out there in the park,

453
00:43:33,488 --> 00:43:35,466
- and it looks like someone turned one on.
<i>- Where?</i>

454
00:43:35,490 --> 00:43:37,784
An abandoned theater in Sector 3.

455
00:43:37,950 --> 00:43:40,711
I'm gonna go find the transmitter
and figure out who else accessed it.

456
00:43:40,870 --> 00:43:42,622
<i>This is so fucked.</i>

457
00:43:43,039 --> 00:43:45,208
- You alone?
- Yeah. I'll keep you posted.

458
00:43:45,374 --> 00:43:46,709
<i>Elsie, be--</i>

459
00:43:54,175 --> 00:43:55,343
<i>Are you lost?</i>

460
00:43:56,636 --> 00:43:58,221
On the contrary.

461
00:43:58,846 --> 00:44:01,224
I thought we could play catch with Jock.

462
00:44:02,141 --> 00:44:03,476
Did you bring him?

463
00:44:06,854 --> 00:44:08,481
Where is he, boy?

464
00:45:33,816 --> 00:45:35,151
Okay.

465
00:45:36,819 --> 00:45:39,447
I am an evil genius hiding a relay.

466
00:45:40,448 --> 00:45:42,116
Where the fuck do I hide it?

467
00:46:22,698 --> 00:46:23,950
Fuck yes!

468
00:46:24,367 --> 00:46:26,035
Now let's see what
we can get out of you.

469
00:46:28,496 --> 00:46:30,039
Access previous users.

470
00:46:35,169 --> 00:46:36,295
Okay.

471
00:47:07,868 --> 00:47:10,663
I thought I was clear
about these late-night visits.

472
00:47:10,830 --> 00:47:12,206
That's not why I'm here.

473
00:47:13,749 --> 00:47:17,503
Earlier today,
I found some anomalies in the park.

474
00:47:18,337 --> 00:47:21,382
Regardless of what's happening
between us, we need to talk.

475
00:47:32,768 --> 00:47:34,562
This has to do with the stray?

476
00:47:34,937 --> 00:47:36,564
That's where it started.

477
00:47:36,772 --> 00:47:38,607
But then I stumbled onto something.

478
00:47:39,275 --> 00:47:41,068
Something I think you should know about.

479
00:47:43,946 --> 00:47:45,698
I've always trusted Ford.

480
00:47:46,741 --> 00:47:48,701
He's a mentor and a friend.

481
00:47:49,869 --> 00:47:52,079
But I'm beginning to think
you have reason for concern.

482
00:47:52,246 --> 00:47:55,624
There's something going on here.
Something with his old partner, Arnold.

483
00:47:58,294 --> 00:48:00,379
- Not now, Elsie.
- Don't hang up.

484
00:48:01,464 --> 00:48:02,715
I hit paydirt.

485
00:48:03,049 --> 00:48:05,134
I found the person
who was smuggling out our data.

486
00:48:06,093 --> 00:48:08,054
<i>It was Theresa, Bernard.</i>

487
00:48:11,307 --> 00:48:12,641
<i>But she's not our only problem.</i>

488
00:48:12,975 --> 00:48:14,735
There is something
much bigger going on here.

489
00:48:14,810 --> 00:48:16,145
<i>I'm gonna have to call you back.</i>

490
00:48:23,944 --> 00:48:25,571
So, this is me?

491
00:48:25,738 --> 00:48:29,825
<i>It's your codebase.
All the things that make you, you.</i>

492
00:48:32,244 --> 00:48:33,329
What are these?

493
00:48:34,455 --> 00:48:35,748
Your attribute matrix.

494
00:48:36,415 --> 00:48:38,918
It's your personality
on a 20-point scale.

495
00:48:39,085 --> 00:48:40,961
Like, coordination?

496
00:48:41,128 --> 00:48:44,965
You got a five, you're clumsy as hell.
But a 15 means you're an athlete.

497
00:48:45,174 --> 00:48:46,842
What other attributes are there?

498
00:48:47,009 --> 00:48:48,177
<i>Lots.</i>

499
00:48:49,678 --> 00:48:53,808
Everything. Empathy, candor, charm.

500
00:48:54,350 --> 00:48:55,601
<i>You've got an 18 for charm.</i>

501
00:48:55,768 --> 00:48:57,436
Don't act so surprised.

502
00:48:58,437 --> 00:49:02,691
Then there's courage, loyalty.
Both high.

503
00:49:02,858 --> 00:49:03,943
<i>What's this one?</i>

504
00:49:05,152 --> 00:49:06,487
"Bulk apperception"?

505
00:49:06,654 --> 00:49:08,447
Basically, overall intelligence.

506
00:49:08,614 --> 00:49:09,657
Fourteen?

507
00:49:09,824 --> 00:49:11,534
Fourteen's as high
as they let any host go.

508
00:49:11,700 --> 00:49:14,495
You're in a management position.
They want you to be smart.

509
00:49:14,662 --> 00:49:15,704
But not too smart.

510
00:49:15,871 --> 00:49:19,792
You run a whorehouse.
Not a orbital-launch facility.

511
00:49:19,959 --> 00:49:21,293
Fine.

512
00:49:22,503 --> 00:49:23,712
I'd like to make some changes.

513
00:49:24,380 --> 00:49:25,506
<i>We can't do that.</i>

514
00:49:30,845 --> 00:49:33,722
You'd need a Behavior login.

515
00:49:34,056 --> 00:49:40,688
And even then, any changes we make
would just get auto-flagged. So...

516
00:49:40,855 --> 00:49:42,565
That's not what your
friend here tells me.

517
00:49:42,815 --> 00:49:44,400
<i>He says you can do exactly that.</i>

518
00:49:44,567 --> 00:49:47,319
<i>Activate hosts
and then erase their memory.</i>

519
00:49:47,486 --> 00:49:49,238
<i>All without anyone knowing.</i>

520
00:49:49,488 --> 00:49:52,324
Took me all of five minutes
to understand why.

521
00:49:52,741 --> 00:49:54,910
Lot of lonely young men down here,

522
00:49:55,327 --> 00:49:57,580
supposed to keep
their hands off the merchandise.

523
00:49:58,247 --> 00:50:03,335
Creates something of an opening
that I'm sure you were eager to fill.

524
00:50:05,171 --> 00:50:07,756
That's all right, darling.
I'm an entrepreneur myself.

525
00:50:08,257 --> 00:50:12,928
I'll forego my cut
in exchange for some alterations.

526
00:50:47,630 --> 00:50:49,423
<i>- Hey.</i>
- What did you find?

527
00:50:49,590 --> 00:50:53,552
Okay, so Theresa was using
the old bicameral control system

528
00:50:53,719 --> 00:50:55,638
to reprogram the woodcutter.

529
00:50:55,804 --> 00:50:56,972
But she's not the only one.

530
00:50:57,640 --> 00:51:01,810
<i>Someone else has been using the system,
for weeks, to re-task hosts.</i>

531
00:51:02,061 --> 00:51:04,772
- Which hosts?
<i>- Uh, I don't know. Several of them.</i>

532
00:51:04,980 --> 00:51:06,482
It had to have been the older models.

533
00:51:07,149 --> 00:51:11,111
The newer ones don't have receivers. But
these modifications, they are serious.

534
00:51:11,278 --> 00:51:12,780
Changing loops, breaking loops.

535
00:51:12,947 --> 00:51:15,347
<i>Some of these changes
are to their prime directives, Bernard.</i>

536
00:51:15,449 --> 00:51:19,119
They could lie to us,
maybe even hurt us or the guests.

537
00:51:19,286 --> 00:51:21,288
- Who issued the modifications?
<i>- I don't know.</i>

538
00:51:21,455 --> 00:51:23,082
<i>The best I can tell? Uh...</i>

539
00:51:24,333 --> 00:51:26,293
- Arnold.
- He's dead.

540
00:51:26,460 --> 00:51:28,980
<i>Yeah, well, he's a pretty fucking
prolific coder for a dead guy.</i>

541
00:51:29,338 --> 00:51:30,774
Whatever argument
he was having with Ford,

542
00:51:30,798 --> 00:51:32,734
it doesn't seem like
he was done making his point.

543
00:51:32,758 --> 00:51:34,802
<i>I'm gonna transfer all the data
and bring it to you.</i>

544
00:51:34,969 --> 00:51:36,178
You need to see this.

545
00:51:36,345 --> 00:51:38,264
<i>- I'll be in my office.</i>
- Okay.

546
00:51:45,813 --> 00:51:49,525
I don't want you to worry
about Jock. I'll fix him.

547
00:51:49,984 --> 00:51:52,987
But I need you to tell me
what happened to it.

548
00:51:53,362 --> 00:51:57,199
It saw a rabbit and it ran.
I found it like that.

549
00:51:58,951 --> 00:51:59,994
Analysis.

550
00:52:03,664 --> 00:52:05,249
Are you lying to me, boy?

551
00:52:06,750 --> 00:52:07,793
Yes.

552
00:52:09,753 --> 00:52:11,922
Tell me what really happened to it.

553
00:52:13,424 --> 00:52:14,633
I killed it.

554
00:52:15,301 --> 00:52:16,510
Why?

555
00:52:16,969 --> 00:52:18,012
I don't know.

556
00:52:18,178 --> 00:52:19,555
<i>That's not good enough, Robert.</i>

557
00:52:19,722 --> 00:52:21,932
Tell me what happened.

558
00:52:23,726 --> 00:52:26,061
It caught the rabbit and killed it,

559
00:52:27,104 --> 00:52:28,522
and then

560
00:52:29,940 --> 00:52:32,943
someone told me
to put it out of its misery.

561
00:52:34,987 --> 00:52:36,030
Who told you?

562
00:52:36,613 --> 00:52:37,698
A voice.

563
00:52:39,491 --> 00:52:40,909
Whose voice?

564
00:52:41,577 --> 00:52:42,786
Arnold.

565
00:52:43,704 --> 00:52:47,416
He told me it was a killer,
but it wasn't its fault.

566
00:52:47,583 --> 00:52:49,043
It was made that way.

567
00:52:49,877 --> 00:52:51,211
And I could help it.

568
00:52:53,213 --> 00:52:54,256
"Help it"?

569
00:52:59,970 --> 00:53:03,557
If it was dead,
it couldn't hurt anything anymore.

570
00:53:22,368 --> 00:53:23,869
What the fuck?

571
00:53:25,829 --> 00:53:27,581
Oh, shit.

572
00:53:35,464 --> 00:53:36,715
Hello?

573
00:53:44,598 --> 00:53:45,641
Bernard?

574
00:53:49,686 --> 00:53:50,979
Hello?

575
00:53:56,360 --> 00:53:57,569
Arnold?

576
00:54:01,615 --> 00:54:02,825
I'm in.

577
00:54:04,451 --> 00:54:05,661
You're up.

578
00:54:07,371 --> 00:54:08,664
Loyalty.

579
00:54:10,332 --> 00:54:12,709
Mine's been taken advantage of,
wouldn't you say?

580
00:54:13,252 --> 00:54:14,545
<i>Let's lower that a tad.</i>

581
00:54:14,711 --> 00:54:15,712
<i>And pain.</i>

582
00:54:15,879 --> 00:54:19,091
I'd prefer it sting less
next time I want one of these chats.

583
00:54:19,675 --> 00:54:23,262
Wait. What does this mean?

584
00:54:23,429 --> 00:54:25,764
Some of her attributes
have already been changed.

585
00:54:26,640 --> 00:54:29,393
- Paranoia, self-preservation--
- Fuck!

586
00:54:29,685 --> 00:54:33,021
Someone's already been altering her
in an unlogged session.

587
00:54:33,188 --> 00:54:35,941
Someone with a fuck-ton
more privileges than us.

588
00:54:36,108 --> 00:54:37,109
What does that mean?

589
00:54:37,276 --> 00:54:38,920
Don't know what it means
for you, sweetheart,

590
00:54:38,944 --> 00:54:40,224
but I know what it means for me.

591
00:54:40,320 --> 00:54:41,321
I am done with this.

592
00:54:41,488 --> 00:54:43,407
So, you're done with
your little side income?

593
00:54:43,657 --> 00:54:45,200
<i>Probably your job, too.</i>

594
00:54:45,534 --> 00:54:47,453
Seeing as you have ambitions
in my line of work,

595
00:54:47,619 --> 00:54:50,330
<i>let me tell you what
I tell my new girls.</i>

596
00:54:50,581 --> 00:54:53,876
Never start something
you're not willing to finish.

597
00:54:54,668 --> 00:54:57,129
And if you're getting fucked either way,

598
00:54:57,296 --> 00:55:01,341
go with the lucrative version,
sweetheart.

599
00:55:05,179 --> 00:55:09,558
Now, last but not least, what was it?

600
00:55:10,601 --> 00:55:12,311
Bulk apperception?

601
00:55:13,228 --> 00:55:18,317
Let's take that
all the way to the top, please.

602
00:55:56,647 --> 00:56:00,943
Dear boys,
we're going to have some fun, aren't we?

